{{coord|45|37|40|N|122|24|16|W|region:US_type:airport_scale:10000|display=title}} {{Infobox Airport | name = Grove Field | image = | FAA = 1W1 | type = Public | owner = Port of Camas - Washougal | operator = | city-served = [[Camas, Washington]] | location = | elevation-f = 429 | elevation-m = 131 | website = | r1-number = 7/25 | r1-length-f = 2,710 | r1-length-m = 826 | r1-surface = [[Asphalt]] | stat-year = 2007 | stat1-header = Aircraft operations | stat1-data = 10,000 | stat2-header = Based aircraft | stat2-data = 86 | footnotes = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration]]<ref name=FAA>{{FAA-airport|ID=1W1|use=PU|own=PU|site=26130.*A}}, effective 2007-12-20</ref> }}
'''Grove Field''' {{airport codes|||1W1}} is a public [[airport]] located three miles (5&nbsp;km) north of the [[central business district]] of [[Camas, Washington|Camas]], a city in [[Clark County, Washington]], [[United States]].<ref name=FAA /> It is located near [[Lacamas Lake]] which has a [[seaplane]] base. Due to the closing of [[Evergreen Field]], many aircraft have moved to Grove Field.
== Facilities and aircraft == Grove Field covers an area of {{convert|23|acre|ha}} which contains one [[runway]] (7/25) with a 2,710 x 40&nbsp;ft (826 x 12 m) [[asphalt]] pavement. For the 12-month period ending May 31, 2007, the airport had 10,000 [[general aviation]] aircraft operations, an average of 27 per day. At that time there were 86 aircraft based at this airport: 99% single-engine and 1% multi-engine.<ref name=FAA /> Flight training, aircraft rental and minor maintenance services are available at Grove.<ref>{{cite web|title=Camas Washougal Aviation Association - Services|url=http://www.cwaagrovefield.org/services|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306022447/http://www.cwaagrovefield.org/services|archivedate=2012-03-06|df=}}</ref>
==History== The air field is named for Ward Grove who built the airfield in 1945. Grove moved to [[Vancouver, Washington]] in 1924 and learned to fly in [[Portland, Oregon]] at the Rankin Flying School operated by [[Tex Rankin]]. During [[World War II]], Grove taught flying in California and returned to Clark County, Washington after the war.The [[Port of Camas-Washougal]] bought the airstrip from him in 1961 and in 1984, the Port Commission voted to name the field in his honor. Grove died in 1993.<ref>Jolotta, Pat, "Naming Clark County, Vancouver Historical Society, 1993, p. 24</ref> A fire on October 6, 2014, did $1 million in damage to 10 hangars at the airport.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Kasia|title=Grove Field Airport hanger fire sparked by electrical failure, fire investigators say. The mooneys Cessna 180 was lost in the fire which is a sad topic for all of them. |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/clark-county/index.ssf/2014/10/grove_field_airport_hanger_fir.html|accessdate=15 October 2014|work=The Oregonian|date=October 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Kasia|title=Fire crews respond to 2-alarm fire at at(sic) Grove Field Airport|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/clark-county/index.ssf/2014/10/fire_crews_respond_to_2-alarm.html|accessdate=15 October 2014|work=The Oregonian|date=October 6, 2014}}</ref>
